review_comments.body:
When the user lacks permission for checklist templates, only the menu item is hidden. The Templates panel remains server-visible, so `OnHandleAngularPanel` will still register the `checklisttemplates.bundle` and the client can potentially activate the panel. Consider also setting `pnlTemplates.Visible = false` (and/or guarding `OnHandleAngularPanel`) when `CanViewRecord(...ChecklistTemplate)` is false to avoid loading the bundle/UI for unauthorized users.
```suggestion
                mnuTemplates.Visible = false;
                pnlTemplates.Visible = false;
```

`.common-is-required` hardcodes a hex colour and explicitly sets Open Sans. Colours should come from Default.css variables (e.g. `var(--red-red)`), and setting Open Sans here is redundant because it’s already applied globally.
```suggestion
    color: var(--red-red);
    font-size: 14px;
```

In the no-access branch, `pnlTemplates.Visible` is only set to `false` when `GetListDefinitionByIdWithUDFs(...) != null`. That doesn’t match the intent in the comment (prevent the Angular bundle from being added when the user can’t access templates) and can still allow the templates panel to be treated as visible and have `checklisttemplates.bundle` registered. Consider setting `pnlTemplates.Visible = false` unconditionally whenever `mnuTemplates.Visible = false` (or otherwise gate the bundle strictly on the same permission check).
```suggestion
                // Keep the templates panel hidden whenever the user cannot access checklist templates
                // so the Angular bundle is not added for an unauthorized user.
                pnlTemplates.Visible = false;
```

